<DOC><DOCNO> AP890221-0105 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1213EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0504 02-21 0737</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0504,0750</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms, Tornadoes Lash Gulf Coast, Bring Floods</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with wind damage in North Carolina,new twister sightings, Georgia outages, other details. Pickup 8th graf,`Several roads...</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A storm centered over western Kentucky today lashed Gulf Coaststates with severe thunderstorms and tornadoes and caused renewedflooding in parts of the Ohio and Tennessee valleys.   Tornadoes hit several parts of northwest Alabama and centralLouisiana, downing power lines, throwing mobile homes and knockingtrees on cars. No serious injuries were reported. School wascanceled today in Alabama's Houston County due to the poor weatherand road conditions.   In North Carolina, tornado-like winds flipped mobile homes inMoore County, injuring four people, tore off a roof of a school andoverturned several small planes in Anson County, authorities said.No children in the school were hurt.   Twisters also were sighted in east-central Mississippi. Heavyrain accompanied the thunderstorms and caused flash floods inAlabama and Louisiana.   Rainfall measured from 3 to 7 inches Monday in Rapides Parish incentral Louisiana, where twisters hit in seven locations, said BillGodron, the parish's civil defense director. Parts of the FloridaPanhandle had more than 3} inches of rain in the six hours ended at1 a.m. EST. Tupelo, Miss., received just over 3 inches of rain inthe period.   Golfball-size hail pelted Fort Walton Beach on the FloridaPanhandle.   Wind gusting to 80 mph downed trees and power lines in Jackson,Miss., Monday evening, knocking out power to several thousand homes.Strong winds also led to power outages in Birmingham, Ala., andsouthwest Georgia, early today.   Several roads were flooded in central Tennessee, where more than2{ inches of rain fell Monday. The Ohio River rose over its banksfrom Louisville, Ky., to Cairo at the southern tip of Illinois.   Flash flood watches were in effect in northern Mississippi,northwest Alabama, Tennessee, parts of Kentucky and West Virginia,southwest Virginia and southern Ohio.   Rain was widespread early today along the East Coast from theCarolinas to Connecticut.   In the Midwest, a band of snow stretched from southern Michiganto Iowa and northern Missouri. Quincy in western Illinois received 7inches. Snow advisories were posted for northern and centralIllinois and southern Michigan, and a winter storm watch was ineffect for northern Maine.   Light snow also fell on the central and northern Plains.   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms in much ofthe East, including the Atlantic states, the central and easternGulf Coast, the Tennessee and Ohio valleys and the lower MississippiValley; thunderstorms from Mississippi to the Atlantic Coast betweenSouth Carolina and northern Florida; rain along the northern PacificCoast; snow in Illinois and the upper Great Lakes region, northernMaine, Montana and Wyoming.   Highs were forecast to be in the teens and 20s from westernMontana across the northern Plains and the upper Mississippi Valleyto western portions of the upper Great Lakes; the 30s and 40s inmuch of Nevada and Idaho, the central Rockies, the central Plains,the Ohio Valley, the remainder of the Great Lakes and northern NewEngland; the 50s and 60s along the Pacific Coast, southern Nevada,the southern Rockies, Texas, the Gulf Coast, the Tennessee Valley,the mid-Atlantic coast and southern New England; the 70s in SouthernCalifornia and southern Arizona; and the 70s and 80s in Florida,southern Georgia and the coast of the Carolinas.   At 2 a.m. EST, temperatures ranged from 1 below zero at GrandForks, N.D., to 76 degrees at Key West Naval Air Station and Miami,Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 47 rain; Boston 36 rain; Buffalo 34 rain;Charleston, S.C. 66 foggy; Cincinnati 49 rain; Cleveland 38 rain;Detroit 33 snow; Miami 75 fair; New York 43 rain; Philadelphia 40drizzle; Pittsburgh 45 rain; Portland, Maine 34 cloudy; Washington39 drizzle.   _Central: Bismarck 11 fair; Chicago 29 snow; Dallas-Fort Worth 45cloudy; Denver 26 partly cloudy; Des Moines 22 snow; Indianapolis 37foggy; Kansas City 26 snow; Minneapolis-St. Paul 16 cloudy;Nashville 55 rain; New Orleans 71 cloudy; St. Louis 32 foggy.   _West: Albuquerque 36 fair; Anchorage 23 cloudy; Las Vegas 51fair; Los Angeles 52 foggy; Phoenix 61 fair; Salt Lake City 32partly cloudy; San Diego 54 fair; San Francisco 52 partly cloudy;Seattle 43 fair.   _Canada: Montreal 30 foggy; Toronto 32 snow.</TEXT></DOC>